FlavorText: It tosses its enemies around with agility. It uses all its limbs to fight in its own unique style.

Name: Infernape
FlavorText: It uses unique fighting moves with fire on its hands and feet. It will take on any opponent.

Name: Piplup
FlavorText: Prefers cold climes and appears along coasts. It’s an adorable little thing—as cute as any child—but it’s also prideful, unwilling to accept handouts from people.

Name: Piplup
FlavorText: It lives along the shore in northern countries. A skilled swimmer, it dives for over 10 minutes while hunting.

Name: Piplup
FlavorText: Because it is very proud, it hates accepting food from people. Its thick down guards it from cold.

Name: Piplup
FlavorText: It doesn’t like to be taken care of. It’s difficult to bond with since it won’t listen to its Trainer.

Name: Piplup
FlavorText: A poor walker, it often falls down. However, its strong pride makes it puff up its chest without a care.

Name: Piplup
FlavorText: It lives along shores in northern countries. A skilled swimmer, it dives for over 10 minutes to hunt.

Name: Prinplup
FlavorText: It swims gracefully through the frigid sea and sings with a voice like the roaring tide. It has powerful, sturdy wings and dignity to match.

Name: Prinplup
FlavorText: Its wings deliver wicked blows that snap even the thickest of trees. It searches for prey in icy seas.

Name: Prinplup
FlavorText: It lives alone, away from others. Apparently, every one of them believes it is the most important.

Name: Prinplup
FlavorText: It lives a solitary life. Its wings deliver wicked blows that can snap even the thickest of trees.

Name: Prinplup
FlavorText: Because every Prinplup considers itself to be the most important, they can never form a group.

Name: Empoleon
FlavorText: Since ancient times, it has been revered by the people of Hisui, who call it the Master of the Waves. Its wings are a match for even master-crafted blades.

Name: Empoleon
FlavorText: It swims as fast as a jet boat. The edges of its wings are sharp and can slice apart drifting ice.

Name: Empoleon
FlavorText: The three horns that extend from its beak attest to its power. The leader has the biggest horns.

Name: Empoleon
FlavorText: If anyone were to hurt its pride, it would slash them with wings that can cleave through an ice floe.

Name: Empoleon
FlavorText: It avoids unnecessary disputes, but it will decimate anything that threatens its pride.

Name: Bibarel
FlavorText: Bibarel fur repels water and is also a fantastic material for heat retention. These Pokémon create dams on rivers to live in.

Name: Bibarel
FlavorText: While its movements out of water are sluggish, it can swim as fast as any Feebas.

Name: Bibarel
FlavorText: It makes its nest by damming streams with bark and mud. It is known as an industrious worker.

Name: Bibarel
FlavorText: It busily makes its nest with stacks of branches and roots it has cut up with its sharp incisors.

Name: Bibarel
FlavorText: A river dammed by Bibarel will never overflow its banks, which is appreciated by people nearby.

Name: Budew
FlavorText: When the sun’s light strengthens, the bud atop this Pokémon’s head opens. This is a sign to the people that the harsh winter is over, and the season of budding has begun.

Name: Budew
FlavorText: It lives alongside clear ponds. It scatters pollen that induces harsh sneezing and runny noses.

Name: Budew
FlavorText: Over the winter, it closes its bud and endures the cold. In spring, the bud opens and releases pollen.

Name: Budew
FlavorText: This Pokémon is highly sensitive to temperature changes. When its bud starts to open, that means spring is right around the corner.

Name: Budew
FlavorText: The pollen it releases contains poison. If this Pokémon is raised on clean water, the poison’s toxicity is increased.

Name: Budew
FlavorText: When it feels the sun’s warm touch, it opens its bud to release pollen. It lives alongside clear pools.

Name: Budew
FlavorText: Sensitive to changing temperatures, the bud blooms when it’s warm, releasing toxic pollen.

Name: Budew
FlavorText: Sensitive to changing temperature, the bud is said to bloom when it feels the sun’s warm touch.

Name: Roserade
FlavorText: Hidden within the bouquet on each hand are thorned whips loaded with virulent poison. Roserade moves gracefully as it corners its prey and mercilessly lashes them with its whips.

Name: Roserade
FlavorText: With the movements of a dancer, it strikes with whips that are densely lined with poison thorns.

Name: Roserade
FlavorText: It attracts prey with a sweet aroma, then downs it with thorny whips hidden in its arms.

Name: Roserade
FlavorText: The poison in its right hand is quick acting. The poison in its left hand is slow acting. Both are life threatening.

Name: Roserade
FlavorText: After captivating opponents with its sweet scent, it lashes them with its thorny whips.

Name: Roserade
FlavorText: Luring prey with a sweet scent, it uses poison whips on its arms to poison, bind, and finish off the prey.

Name: Roserade
FlavorText: Each of its hands contains different toxins, but both hands can jab with near-fatal power.

Name: Roserade
FlavorText: Its sweet aroma attracts prey. Then it spews poison. The more toxic it is, the sweeter its aroma.

Name: Wormadam
FlavorText: The cloak—fashioned from plant matter—has merged with the Pokémon and is now part of the body, like fur or skin. I suspect this fusion is an effect of the energy involved in evolution.

Name: Wormadam
FlavorText: Its appearance changes depending on where it evolved. The materials on hand become a part of its body.

Name: Wormadam
FlavorText: When Burmy evolves, its cloak becomes a part of its body. Wormadam’s cloak is never shed.

Name: Wormadam
FlavorText: When Burmy evolved, its cloak became a part of this Pokémon’s body. The cloak is never shed.

Name: Wormadam
FlavorText: When evolving, its body takes in surrounding materials. As a result, there are many body variations.

Name: Wormadam
FlavorText: It is said that a WORMADAM that evolves on a cold day will have a thicker cloak.

Name: Buizel
FlavorText: It inflates its flotation sac, keeping its face above water in order to watch for prey movement.

Name: Buizel
FlavorText: It spins its two tails like a screw to propel itself through water. The tails also slice clinging seaweed.

Name: Buizel
FlavorText: It moves freely in the water by spinning its forked tail for propulsion. The resemblance to the screw of a steamboat is coincidental.

Name: Buizel
FlavorText: It swims by rotating its two tails like a screw. When it dives, its flotation sac collapses.

Name: Buizel
FlavorText: When air fills the flotation sac on its neck, the sac balloons like an inner tube. This Pokémon floats with its head out of the water.

Name: Buizel
FlavorText: It inflates the flotation sac around its neck and pokes its head out of the water to see what is going on.

Name: Buizel
FlavorText: It has a flotation sac that is like an inflatable collar. It floats on water with its head out.

Name: Floatzel
FlavorText: It is a common sight around fishing ports. It is known to rescue people and help fishers carry what they caught.

Name: Floatzel
FlavorText: With its flotation sac inflated, it can carry people on its back. It deflates the sac before it dives.

Name: Floatzel
FlavorText: Has a long, rather splendid flotation sac, which prevents Floatzel from drowning even in stormy seas. One might glimpse this species around fishing hamlets from time to time.

Name: Floatzel
FlavorText: Its flotation sac developed as a result of pursuing aquatic prey. Floatzel carries people as if it were a rubber raft.

Name: Floatzel
FlavorText: It floats using its well-developed flotation sac. It assists in the rescues of drowning people.

Name: Floatzel
FlavorText: Its flotation sac developed as a result of pursuing aquatic prey. It can double as a rubber raft.

Name: Floatzel
FlavorText: It is a common sight around fishing ports. It is known to rescue people and carry off prey.

Name: Cherubi
FlavorText: Once the fruit growing alongside the main body is large and plump, Cherubi will use the nutrients within to evolve. The fruit then detaches, becoming nourishment for other creatures.

Name: Cherubi
FlavorText: Sunlight colors it red. When the small ball is drained of nutrients and shriveled, evolution is near.

Name: Cherubi
FlavorText: The small ball holds the nutrients needed for evolution. Apparently, it is very sweet and tasty.

Name: Cherubi
FlavorText: The deeper a Cherubi’s red, the more nutrients it has stockpiled in its body. And the sweeter and tastier its small ball!

Name: Cherubi
FlavorText: It nimbly dashes about to avoid getting pecked by bird Pokémon that would love to make off with its small, nutrient-rich storage ball.

Name: Cherubi
FlavorText: It evolves by sucking the energy out of the small ball where it had been storing nutrients.

Name: Cherubi
FlavorText: Sunlight colors it red. When the small ball is drained of nutrients, it shrivels to herald evolution.

Name: Cherubi
FlavorText: The small ball is not only filled with nutrients, it is also tasty. Starly try to peck it off.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: Cheerfully active on sunny days. Immediately closes its petals and becomes immobile once the sun becomes hidden, however.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: The faint scent that emanates from its full blossom entices bug Pokémon to it.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: After absorbing plenty of sunlight, Cherrim takes this form. It’s full of energy while it’s like this, and its liveliness will go on until sundown.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: Its folded petals are pretty tough. Bird Pokémon can peck at them all they want, and Cherrim won’t be bothered at all.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: As a bud, it barely moves. It sits still, placidly waiting for sunlight to appear.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: Motionless, save for the occasional quiver. A rich array of Pokémon can be found gathered around it, drawn by the scent exuded from Cherrim’s folded petals.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: It is docile as a bud and turns cheerful when it blooms. It folds back into a bud if sunlight wanes.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: It blooms during times of strong sunlight. The Pokémon tries to make up for everything it endured as a bud.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: If it senses strong sunlight, it opens its folded petals to absorb the sun’s rays with its whole body.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: During times of strong sunlight, its bud blooms, its petals open fully, and it becomes very active.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: It is docile as a bud, but turns cheerful when it blooms. It folds back into a bud if sunlight wanes.

Name: Cherrim
FlavorText: It blooms during times of strong sunlight. It tries to make up for everything it endured as a bud.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: It oozes a purple fluid to deter enemies. Apparently, there are more West Sea Shellos now than there were in the past.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: It used to have a shell on its back long ago. This species is closely related to Pokémon like Shellder.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: This Pokémon can often be seen along seashores. It’s capable of spending a limited amount of time on land.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: A recently published research paper states that this form of Shellos is gradually decreasing in number.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: Found in abundance on seashores bordering cold waters. When pressed upon, the Pokémon will secrete from its body’s surface a purple fluid that will stain one’s clothes.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: Its appearance changes depending on the environment. One theory suggests that living in cold seas causes Shellos to take on this form.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: There’s speculation that its appearance is determined by what it eats, but the truth remains elusive.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: Scientists interested in its great regenerative capabilities are currently analyzing the materials from which its cells are made.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: When it senses danger, it gushes a purple liquid. Some theories suggest this liquid is a greasy sweat induced by stress.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: The difference in color from one Shellos to another seems to be a result of their diet. No large changes can be seen in their capabilities.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: Shellos lives in the sea and feasts on plankton. The lovelier the ocean where Shellos resides, the more vibrant its color becomes.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: Subjecting this Pokémon to a strong force causes it to secrete a strange purple fluid. Though harmless, the fluid is awfully sticky.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: This Pokémon’s habitat shapes its physique. According to some theories, life in warm ocean waters causes this variation to develop.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: When it senses danger, a purple liquid oozes out of it. The liquid is thought to be something like greasy sweat.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: While they normally live in the sea, they can function on land, too, until their skin dries out.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: Purple mucus sticks to the hands of anyone who touches it. Take care, as the substance is troublesome to wash off.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: For the most part, it makes its home along the seashore. Its color and form differ according to its habitat and the quality of its food.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: Found in abundance on seashores bordering warm waters. Shellos are unexpectedly friendly and will crawl toward any person they see. Take care not to get coated in mucus!

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: It lives along bodies of water. Its body shape changed to suit its habitat.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: Its colors and shapes differ from region to region. In the Sinnoh region, two types are confirmed.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: Its shape and coloration vary, depending on its habitat.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: Beware of pushing strongly on its squishy body, as it makes a mysterious purple fluid ooze out.

Name: Shellos
FlavorText: It lives along bodies of water. Its body shape has changed to suit its habitat.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: It appears on beaches where the waters are shallow. Once it catches prey, it will slowly melt them with its mucus before slurping them up.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: Its whole body is sticky with mucus. In the past, this form of Gastrodon was by far the more numerous one.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: Fishers say that they didn’t see many of these Pokémon in the past, but this form of Gastrodon is now increasing in number.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: They normally inhabit rocky seashores, but in times of continuous rain, they can sometimes be found in the mountains, far from the sea.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: Found more often on the land than in the sea. More active when it’s cloudy or rainy out than when the weather is fair.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: Its body is covered in a sticky slime. It’s very susceptible to dehydration, so it can’t spend too much time on land.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: It secretes a purple fluid to deter enemies. This fluid isn’t poisonous—instead, it’s super sticky, and once it sticks, it’s very hard to unstick.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: A relative of Shellder and Cloyster, this ocean dweller sometimes comes onto land in search of food.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: When it’s attacked, it gushes a purple liquid that’s not poisonous but makes Gastrodon’s meat bitter and inedible.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: Experiments are being conducted to discover what happens when a Gastrodon is raised in a location other than the sea where it was born.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: A team of researchers is scouring the oceans of the world in search of a Gastrodon in a color never seen before.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: The softness of its body helps disperse the force of impacts, so although its body is uncommonly squishy, it’s also surprisingly resilient.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: Its search for food sometimes leads it onto land, where it leaves behind a sticky trail of slime as it passes through.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: Their shape and color change, depending on their environment and diet. There are many of them at beaches where the waves are calm.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: Long ago, it had a shell on its back. There’s now a vestigial plate on its back that’s hard but thin.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: Plankton, invisible to the naked eye, is its main food source. It comes onto the land periodically, but the reason for this is not known.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: It has strong regenerative capabilities. Even if parts of it are bitten off by fish Pokémon, it will return to normal within a few hours.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: Eats beach sand for nourishment. Should one Gastrodon encounter another of a different color, a fierce battle will inevitably ensue.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: It apparently had a huge shell for protection in ancient times. It lives in shallow tidal pools.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: It has a pliable body without any bones. If any part of its body is torn off, it grows right back.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: When its natural enemy attacks, it oozes purple fluid and escapes.

Name: Gastrodon
FlavorText: Long ago, its entire back was shielded with a sturdy shell. There are traces of it left in its cells.

Name: Carnivine
FlavorText: Though this is a plant Pokémon, it has a gluttonous and unruly temperament. Carnivine attacks its prey with its cavernous maw wide open.

Name: Carnivine
FlavorText: Using its tentacles to hang from branches, it looks like a plant when it is not moving. It awaits prey with its mouth wide open.

Name: Carnivine
FlavorText: It attracts prey with its sweet-smelling saliva, then chomps down. It takes a whole day to eat its prey.

Name: Carnivine
FlavorText: It binds itself to trees in marshes. It attracts prey with its sweet-smelling drool and gulps them down.

Name: Carnivine
FlavorText: It attracts prey with its sweet-smelling saliva, then chomps down. It takes a whole day to eat prey.

Name: Carnivine
FlavorText: Using its tentacles to lash itself to trees, it lies in wait for prey, luring it close with sweet-smelling drool.

Name: Carnivine
FlavorText: It walks around on its tentacles in search of a tree branch where it can dangle down and ambush prey.

Name: Carnivine
FlavorText: Hanging from branches using its tentacles, it looks like a plant. It awaits prey, mouth wide open.

Name: Finneon
FlavorText: It absorbs sunlight with the pink areas of its skin, which then shine. This appears to be a form of camouflage.

Name: Finneon
FlavorText: The line running down its side can store sunlight. It shines vividly at night.

Name: Finneon
FlavorText: What a gorgeous sight this Pokémon is as it swims with its long, pink-painted caudal fins fluttering behind it. Finneon’s beautiful appearance has led to its nickname: “finery fish.”

Name: Finneon
FlavorText: The way its two tail fins flutter while it swims has earned it the nickname Beautifly of the Sea.

Name: Finneon
FlavorText: After long exposure to sunlight, the patterns on its tail fins shine vividly when darkness arrives.

Name: Finneon
FlavorText: It lures in prey with its shining tail fins. It stays near the surface during the day and moves to the depths when night falls.

Name: Finneon
FlavorText: When night falls, their pink patterns begin to shine. They’re popular with divers, so there are resorts that feed them to keep them close.

Name: Finneon
FlavorText: Its double tail fins propel its energetic jumps. When it breaks the surface of the sea, Wingull swoop down to grab it on the fly.

Name: Finneon
FlavorText: Swimming and fluttering its two tail fins, it looks like a BEAUTIFLY. At night, the patterns on its tail fins softly shine.

Name: Finneon
FlavorText: The way its two tail fins flutter while it swims has earned it the nickname “BEAUTIFLY of the Sea.”

Name: Lumineon
FlavorText: Lumineon swimming in the darkness of the deep sea look like stars shining in the night sky.

Name: Lumineon
FlavorText: With its shining light, it lures its prey close. However, the light also happens to attract ferocious fish Pokémon—its natural predators.

Name: Lumineon
FlavorText: Uses its gleaming fins to hunt its prey. The view of Lumineon schooling near the surface of the sea at night is breathtaking— it’s as though there were shining stars right there.

Name: Lumineon
FlavorText: To avoid detection by predators, it crawls along the seafloor using the two fins on its chest.

Name: Lumineon
FlavorText: It lives on the deep-sea floor. It attracts prey by flashing patterns on its four fins.

Name: Lumineon
FlavorText: They traverse the deep waters as if crawling over the seafloor. The fantastic lights of its fins shine like stars in the night sky.

Name: Lumineon
FlavorText: Deep down at the bottom of the ocean, prey is scarce. Lumineon get into fierce disputes with Lanturn over food.

Name: Lumineon
FlavorText: This deep-sea Pokémon lives at the bottom of the sea. Its fins haul it over the seabed in search of its favorite food—Starmie.

Name: Lumineon
FlavorText: It lives on the deep-sea floor. It attracts prey by flashing the patterns on its four tail fins.

Name: Lumineon
FlavorText: It crawls along the seafloor using its long front fins like legs. It competes for food with Lanturn.

Name: Mantyke
FlavorText: Though ball-like in shape, this Pokémon is a proficient swimmer. I have discovered that if a Mantyke spends much time with schools of Remoraid, it will eventually achieve evolution.

Name: Mantyke
FlavorText: Scientists discovered that the distinctive patterns on its back differ by region.

Name: Mantyke
FlavorText: A friendly Pokémon that senses the subtle flows of seawater using its two antennae.

Name: Mantyke
FlavorText: It swims along with a school of Remoraid, and they’ll all fight together to repel attackers.

Name: Mantyke
FlavorText: Mantyke living in Galar seem to be somewhat sluggish. The colder waters of the seas in this region may be the cause.

Name: Mantyke
FlavorText: Mantyke are friendly toward people and will approach boats closely. The patterns on their backs differ depending on their habitat.

Name: Mantyke
FlavorText: It’s highly friendly and easily tamed. Tours that take people swimming with Mantyke are a super-popular beach activity.

Name: Mantyke
FlavorText: When it swims close to the surface of the ocean, people aboard ships are able to observe the pattern on its back.

Name: Mantyke
FlavorText: The pattern on its back varies by region. It often swims in a school of Remoraid.

Name: Mantyke
FlavorText: People organize tours to see this Pokémon frolic and skim the tops of waves with Remoraid.

Name: Mantyke
FlavorText: A friendly Pokémon that captures the subtle flows of seawater using its two antennae.

Name: Snover
FlavorText: Seemingly curious about people, they gather around footsteps they find on snowy mountains.

Name: Snover
FlavorText: During cold seasons, it migrates to the mountain’s lower reaches. It returns to the snow-covered summit in the spring.

Name: Snover
FlavorText: One is likely to encounter this Pokémon while out in the snow. There are stories of Snover appearing in human settlements but doing no harm—rather, they bond with the children.

Name: Snover
FlavorText: In the spring, it grows berries with the texture of frozen treats around its belly.

Name: Snover
FlavorText: It lives on snowy mountains. Having had little contact with humans, it is boldly inquisitive.

Name: Snover
FlavorText: The berries that grow around its belly are like ice pops. Galarian Darumaka absolutely love these berries.

Name: Snover
FlavorText: It lives on snowy mountains. It sinks its legs into the snow to absorb water and keep its own temperature down.

Name: Abomasnow
FlavorText: They appear when the snow flowers bloom. When the petals fall, they retreat to places unknown again.

Name: Abomasnow
FlavorText: It lives a quiet life on mountains that are perpetually covered in snow. It hides itself by whipping up blizzards.

Name: Abomasnow
FlavorText: A powerful Pokémon that can split huge boulders with ease. Dislikes associating with others and chooses to live quietly deep within the mountains, playing with the snow.

Name: Abomasnow
FlavorText: It blankets wide areas in snow by whipping up blizzards. It is also known as the Ice Monster.

Name: Abomasnow
FlavorText: It whips up blizzards in mountains that are always buried in snow. It is the abominable snowman.

Name: Abomasnow
FlavorText: This Pokémon is known to bring blizzards. A shake of its massive body is enough to cause whiteout conditions.

Name: Abomasnow
FlavorText: If it sees any packs of Darumaka going after Snover, it chases them off, swinging its sizable arms like hammers.

Name: Abomasnow
FlavorText: It blankets wide areas in snow by whipping up blizzards. It is also known as “The Ice Monster.”

Name: Tangrowth
FlavorText: Draped with long vines, it resembles a shrub in appearance. It swings bundles of vines as though they were arms, wrapping them around prey to ensnare them.

Name: Tangrowth
FlavorText: It ensnares prey by extending arms made of vines. Losing arms to predators does not trouble it.

Name: Tangrowth
FlavorText: Vine growth is accelerated for Tangrowth living in warm climates. If the vines grow long, Tangrowth shortens them by tearing parts of them off.

Name: Tangrowth
FlavorText: Tangrowth has two arms that it can extend as it pleases. Recent research has shown that these arms are, in fact, bundles of vines.

Name: Tangrowth
FlavorText: Its vines grow so profusely that, in the warm season, you can’t even see its eyes.

Name: Tangrowth
FlavorText: Even if one of its arms is eaten, it’s fine. The Pokémon regenerates quickly and will go right back to normal.

Name: Tangrowth
FlavorText: Its arms are made of plants that bind themselves to things. They grow back right away if cut.

Name: Tangrowth
FlavorText: When it remains still, it appears to be a large shrub. Unsuspecting prey that wander near get ensnared by its vines.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: Use of a strange item caused this Pokémon to evolve. Fireballs launched from the ends of its tubelike arms are hot enough to melt an iron pot in an instant.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: It blasts fireballs of over 3,600 degrees Fahrenheit from the ends of its arms. It lives in volcanic craters.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: Living in the crater of a volcano has caused this Pokémon’s body to resemble its environment—it has an organ similar to a magma chamber.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: When Magmortar inhales deeply, the fire burning in its belly intensifies, rising in temperature to over 3,600 degrees Fahrenheit.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: Magmortar takes down its enemies by shooting fireballs, which burn them to a blackened crisp. It avoids this method when hunting prey.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: There are still quite a few factories that rely on the flames provided by Magmortar to process metals.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: From its arm, it launches fireballs hotter than 3,500 degrees Fahrenheit. Its arm starts to melt when it fires a whole barrage.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: They dwell in volcanic craters. According to what is known, a single pair of male and female Magmortar lives in one volcano.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: It blasts fireballs of over 3,600 degrees Fahrenheit out of its arms. Its breath also sears and sizzles.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: When shooting 3,600 degree F fireballs from its arms, its body takes on a whitish hue from the intense heat.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: When launching 3,600 degrees F fireballs, its body takes on a whitish hue from the intense heat.

Name: Magmortar
FlavorText: It blasts fireballs of over 3,600 degrees F from the ends of its arms. It lives in volcanic craters.

Name: Leafeon
FlavorText: The younger they are, the more they smell like fresh grass. With age, their fragrance takes on the odor of fallen leaves.

Name: Leafeon
FlavorText: When you see Leafeon asleep in a patch of sunshine, you’ll know it is using photosynthesis to produce clean air.

Name: Leafeon
FlavorText: Cells similar to those of plants have been found in its fur. Its hard tail can fell a large tree with one stroke, and the tail’s sharpness exceeds even that of a sword crafted by a master.

Name: Leafeon
FlavorText: Just like a plant, it uses photosynthesis. As a result, it is always enveloped in clear air.

Name: Leafeon
FlavorText: This Pokémon’s tail is blade sharp, with a fantastic cutting edge that can slice right though large trees.

Name: Leafeon
FlavorText: Galarians favor the distinctive aroma that drifts from this Pokémon’s leaves. There’s a popular perfume made using that scent.

Name: Leafeon
FlavorText: It gets its nutrition from photosynthesis. It lives a quiet life deep in forests where clean rivers flow.

Name: Leafeon
FlavorText: Although it doesn’t like disputes, it will sharpen the leaf on its tail into a blade and fight if it has to protect its friends.

Name: Leafeon
FlavorText: Its cellular composition is closer to that of a plant than an animal. It uses photosynthesis to produce its energy supply without eating food.

Name: Leafeon
FlavorText: With cells similar to those of plants, it performs photosynthesis inside its body and creates pure air.

Name: Leafeon
FlavorText: It basically does not fight. With cells similar to those of plants, it can perform photosynthesis.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: This Rotom has possessed a lawn mower. It will mow down grass and flowers, then swagger around with pride at its accomplishments.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: The lawn mower is one of the household appliances that led to the development of the Rotom Dex.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: A form in which Rotom lurks within a misshapen wheelbarrow. The wheelbarrow’s mechanisms are bizarre. It’s a bothersome Pokémon, causing trouble by mowing down grass and trees.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: In this form, Rotom focuses its antics on plants. Any flowers you were growing are going to get mowed down.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: This is Rotom after it’s seized control of a lawn mower that has a special motor. As it mows down grass, it scatters the clippings everywhere.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: The model of washing machine that Rotom can inspirit has been discontinued, so these appliances are now traded at high prices.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: This Rotom has entered a washing machine. It nods with satisfaction after it floods the surrounding area.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: A form in which Rotom lurks within an odd bureau. The bureau’s purpose is unknown. A bothersome Pokémon, causing trouble by splashing cold water everywhere.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: This Rotom has possessed a washing machine that uses a special motor. It blasts out water to get enemies to back down.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: This form of Rotom enjoys coming up with water-based pranks. Be careful with it if you don’t want your room flooded.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: This Rotom has possessed a convection microwave oven. It will sear the surrounding area with its burning heat, then smile in delight.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: If the convection microwave oven is not working properly, then the Rotom inhabiting it will become lethargic.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: A form in which Rotom lurks within a strange cauldron. The cauldron’s origin is unknown. A bothersome Pokémon, causing trouble with the flames it spits.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: This form of Rotom enjoys making mischief by turning up the heat. It will gleefully burn your favorite outfit.

Name: Rotom
FlavorText: This Rotom has possessed a convection microwave oven that uses a special motor. It also has a flair for manipulating flames.

Name: Palkia
FlavorText: It soars across the sky in a form that greatly resembles the creator of all things. Perhaps this imitation of appearance is Palkia’s strategy for gaining Arceus’s powers.

Name: Palkia
FlavorText: This Pokémon is feared as a deity in Hisuian legend. The birth of Palkia was what caused the walls of our world to disappear, creating a sky that spans for infinity.

Name: Palkia
FlavorText: It is said to live in a gap in the spatial dimension parallel to ours. Palkia appears in mythology.

Name: Palkia
FlavorText: It has the ability to distort space. It is described as a deity in Sinnoh-region mythology.

Name: Palkia
FlavorText: It is said to live in a gap in the spatial dimension parallel to ours. It appears in mythology.

Name: Palkia
FlavorText: A legendary Pokémon of Sinnoh. It is said that space becomes more stable with Palkia’s every breath.

Name: Palkia
FlavorText: Its total control over the boundaries of space enable it to transport itself to faraway places or even other dimensions.

Name: Heatran
FlavorText: Stories tell of this Pokémon being birthed from the boiling magma within Mount Coronet. Its molten-steel body holds many mysteries.

Name: Heatran
FlavorText: It dwells in volcanic caves. It digs in with its cross-shaped feet to crawl on ceilings and walls.

Name: Heatran
FlavorText: Boiling blood, like magma, circulates through its body. It makes its dwelling place in volcanic caves.

Name: Heatran
FlavorText: Its body is made of rugged steel. However, it is partially melted in spots because of its own heat.

Name: Phione
FlavorText: Can be seen floating offshore during seasons when the seas are warm. Its azure body blends in with the ocean waters—logic suggests this is a defense mechanism against natural predators.

Name: Phione
FlavorText: A Pokémon that lives in warm seas. It inflates the flotation sac on its head to drift and search for food.

Name: Phione
FlavorText: It drifts in warm seas. It always returns to where it was born, no matter how far it may have drifted.

Name: Phione
FlavorText: When the water warms, they inflate the flotation sac on their heads and drift languidly on the sea in packs.

Name: Manaphy
FlavorText: Rumored to migrate across the oceans and visit Hisui’s coastal waters only rarely. Although Manaphy resembles Phione, it is also quite different. The relation between the two is unclear.

Name: Manaphy
FlavorText: Water makes up 80 percent of its body. This Pokémon is easily affected by its environment.

Name: Manaphy
FlavorText: Born on a cold seafloor, it will swim great distances to return to its birthplace.

Name: Manaphy
FlavorText: It starts its life with a wondrous power that permits it to bond with any kind of Pokémon.

Name: Manaphy
FlavorText: It is born with a wondrous power that lets it bond with any kind of Pokémon.

Name: Manaphy
FlavorText: Water makes up 80% of its body. This Pokémon is easily affected by its environment.

Name: Shaymin
FlavorText: Upon taking in the scent of a particular rare flower, Shaymin is enveloped in light, and its tiny body transforms. I took a whiff of the flower myself, but alas, my body remained unchanged.

Name: Shaymin
FlavorText: When the turning of seasons brings the cruel winter to its end and the joyous people give thanks to the heavens, Shaymin appears and covers the withered land with flowers.

Name: Shaymin
FlavorText: It can dissolve toxins in the air to instantly transform ruined land into a lush field of flowers.

Name: Shaymin
FlavorText: It lives in common flower patches but is rarely noticed. It is often mistaken for a flowering plant when curled up.

Name: Shaymin
FlavorText: The blooming of Gracidea flowers confers the power of flight upon it. Feelings of gratitude are the message it delivers.

Name: Shaymin
FlavorText: The flowers all over its body burst into bloom if it is lovingly hugged and senses gratitude.

Name: Shaymin
FlavorText: The blooming of Gracidea flowers confers the power of flight upon it. Feelings  of gratitude are the message it delivers.

Name: Shaymin
FlavorText: It lives in flower patches and avoids detection by curling up to look like a flowering plant.

Name: Victini
FlavorText: When it shares the infinite energy it creates, that being’s entire body will be overflowing with power.

Name: Victini
FlavorText: This Pokémon brings victory. It is said that Trainers with Victini always win, regardless of the type of encounter.

Name: Victini
FlavorText: It creates an unlimited supply of energy inside its body, which it shares with those who touch it.

Name: Snivy
FlavorText: They photosynthesize by bathing their tails in sunlight. When they are not feeling well, their tails droop.

Name: Snivy
FlavorText: Being exposed to sunlight makes its movements swifter. It uses vines more adeptly than its hands.

Name: Snivy
FlavorText: It is very intelligent and calm. Being exposed to lots of sunlight makes its movements swifter.

Name: Servine
FlavorText: When it gets dirty, its leaves can’t be used in photosynthesis, so it always keeps itself clean.

Name: Servine
FlavorText: It moves along the ground as if sliding. Its swift movements befuddle its foes, and it then attacks with a vine whip.

Name: Servine
FlavorText: They avoid attacks by sinking into the shadows of thick foliage. They retaliate with masterful whipping techniques.

Name: Serperior
FlavorText: It can stop its opponents’ movements with just a glare. It takes in solar energy and boosts it internally.

Name: Serperior
FlavorText: It only gives its all against strong opponents who are not fazed by the glare from Serperior’s noble eyes.

Name: Serperior
FlavorText: They raise their heads to intimidate opponents but only give it their all when fighting a powerful opponent.

Name: Tepig
FlavorText: It loves to eat roasted berries, but sometimes it gets too excited and burns them to a crisp.

Name: Tepig
FlavorText: It can deftly dodge its foe’s attacks while shooting fireballs from its nose. It roasts berries before it eats them.

Name: Tepig
FlavorText: It blows fire through its nose. When it catches a cold, the fire becomes pitch-black smoke instead.

Name: Pignite
FlavorText: When its internal fire flares up, its movements grow sharper and faster. When in trouble, it emits smoke.

Name: Pignite
FlavorText: The more it eats, the more fuel it has to make the fire in its stomach stronger. This fills it with even more power.

Name: Pignite
FlavorText: Whatever it eats becomes fuel for the flame in its stomach. When it is angered, the intensity of the flame increases.

Name: Emboar
FlavorText: It has mastered fast and powerful fighting moves. It grows a beard of fire.

Name: Emboar
FlavorText: It can throw a fire punch by setting its fists on fire with its fiery chin. It cares deeply about its friends.

Name: Emboar
FlavorText: A flaring beard of fire is proof that it is fired up. It is adept at using many different moves.

Name: Oshawott
FlavorText: This Pokémon from the Unova region uses the shell on its belly as a weapon to cut down its foes. Thus, I’ve conferred upon this shell the name “scalchop.”

Name: Oshawott
FlavorText: The scalchop on its stomach isn’t just used for battle—it can be used to break open hard berries as well.

Name: Oshawott
FlavorText: It fights using the scalchop on its stomach. In response to an attack, it retaliates immediately by slashing.

Name: Oshawott
FlavorText: The scalchop on its stomach isn’t just used for battle--it can be used to break open hard berries as well.

Name: Oshawott
FlavorText: The scalchop on its stomach is made from the same elements as claws. It detaches the scalchop for use as a blade.

Name: Dewott
FlavorText: Its exquisite double-scalchop technique is likely the result of daily training, and it can send even masters of the blade fleeing in defeat.

Name: Dewott
FlavorText: As a result of strict training, each Dewott learns different forms for using the scalchops.

Name: Dewott
FlavorText: Strict training is how it learns its flowing double-scalchop technique.

Name: Dewott
FlavorText: Scalchop techniques differ from one Dewott to another. It never neglects maintaining its scalchops.

Name: Samurott
FlavorText: Hard of heart and deft of blade, this rare form of Samurott is a product of the Pokémon’s evolution in the region of Hisui. Its turbulent blows crash into foes like ceaseless pounding waves.

Name: Samurott
FlavorText: One swing of the sword incorporated in its armor can fell an opponent. A simple glare from one of them quiets everybody.

Name: Samurott
FlavorText: In the time it takes a foe to blink, it can draw and sheathe the seamitars attached to its front legs.

Name: Samurott
FlavorText: Part of the armor on its anterior legs becomes a giant sword. Its cry alone is enough to intimidate most enemies.

Name: Pansage
FlavorText: It’s good at finding berries and gathers them from all over. It’s kind enough to share them with friends.

Name: Pansage
FlavorText: It shares the leaf on its head with weary-looking Pokémon. These leaves are known to relieve stress.

Name: Pansage
FlavorText: This Pokémon dwells deep in the forest. Eating a leaf from its head whisks weariness away as if by magic.

Name: Simisage
FlavorText: Ill tempered, it fights by swinging its barbed tail around wildly. The leaf growing on its head is very bitter.

Name: Simisage
FlavorText: It attacks enemies with strikes of its thorn-covered tail. This Pokémon is wild tempered.

Name: Simisage
FlavorText: It strikes its enemies with a thorn-covered tail. The leaf on its head is bitter.

Name: Pansear
FlavorText: This Pokémon lives in caves in volcanoes. The fire within the tuft on its head can reach 600 degrees Fahrenheit.

Name: Pansear
FlavorText: Very intelligent, it roasts berries before eating them. It likes to help people.

Name: Pansear
FlavorText: This Pokémon lives in caves in volcanoes. The fire within the tuft on its head can reach 600° F.

Name: Pansear
FlavorText: When it is angered, the temperature of its head tuft reaches 600° F. It uses its tuft to roast berries.

Name: Simisear
FlavorText: When it gets excited, embers rise from its head and tail and it gets hot. For some reason, it loves sweets.

Name: Simisear
FlavorText: A flame burns inside its body. It scatters embers from its head and tail to sear its opponents.

Name: Simisear
FlavorText: It loves sweets because they become energy for the fire burning inside its body.

Name: Panpour
FlavorText: The water stored inside the tuft on its head is full of nutrients. Plants that receive its water grow large.

Name: Panpour
FlavorText: The water stored inside the tuft on its head is full of nutrients. It waters plants with it using its tail.

Name: Panpour
FlavorText: It does not thrive in dry environments. It keeps itself damp by shooting water stored in its head tuft from its tail.

Name: Simipour
FlavorText: It prefers places with clean water. When its tuft runs low, it replenishes it by siphoning up water with its tail.

Name: Simipour
FlavorText: The high-pressure water expelled from its tail is so powerful, it can destroy a concrete wall.

Name: Simipour
FlavorText: The tuft on its head holds water. When the level runs low, it replenishes the tuft by siphoning up water with its tail.

Name: Tympole
FlavorText: It uses sound waves to communicate with others of its kind. People and other Pokémon species can’t hear its cries of warning.

Name: Tympole
FlavorText: Graceful ripples running across the water’s surface are a sure sign that Tympole are singing in high-pitched voices below.

Name: Tympole
FlavorText: By vibrating its cheeks, it emits sound waves imperceptible to humans. It uses the rhythm of these sounds to talk.

Name: Tympole
FlavorText: By vibrating its cheeks, it emits sound waves imperceptible to humans and warns others of danger.

Name: Tympole
FlavorText: They warn others of danger by vibrating their cheeks to create a high-pitched sound.

Name: Palpitoad
FlavorText: On occasion, their cries are sublimely pleasing to the ear. Palpitoad with larger lumps on their bodies can sing with a wider range of sounds.

Name: Palpitoad
FlavorText: It weakens its prey with sound waves intense enough to cause headaches, then entangles them with its sticky tongue.

Name: Palpitoad
FlavorText: It lives in the water and on land. It uses its long, sticky tongue to immobilize its opponents.

Name: Palpitoad
FlavorText: When they vibrate the bumps on their heads, they can make waves in water or earthquake-like vibrations on land.

Name: Palpitoad
FlavorText: It lives in the water and on land. It uses its long, sticky tongue to capture prey.

Name: Seismitoad
FlavorText: This Pokémon is popular among the elderly, who say the vibrations of its lumps are great for massages.

Name: Seismitoad
FlavorText: The vibrating of the bumps all over its body causes earthquake-like tremors. Seismitoad and Croagunk are similar species.

Name: Seismitoad
FlavorText: They shoot paralyzing liquid from their head bumps. They use vibration to hurt their opponents.

Name: Seismitoad
FlavorText: It increases the power of its punches by vibrating the bumps on its fists. It can turn a boulder to rubble with one punch.

Name: Seismitoad
FlavorText: By putting power into its bumps, it creates vibrations and increases the power of its punches.

Name: Sewaddle
FlavorText: Since this Pokémon makes its own clothes out of leaves, it is a popular mascot for fashion designers.

Name: Sewaddle
FlavorText: This Pokémon makes clothes for itself. It chews up leaves and sews them with sticky thread extruded from its mouth.

Name: Sewaddle
FlavorText: Leavanny dress it in clothes they made for it when it hatched. It hides its head in its hood while it is sleeping.

Name: Swadloon
FlavorText: It protects itself from the cold by wrapping up in leaves. It stays on the move, eating leaves in forests.

Name: Swadloon
FlavorText: Forests where Swadloon live have superb foliage because the nutrients they make from fallen leaves nourish the plant life.

Name: Swadloon
FlavorText: Preferring dark, damp places, it spends the entire day eating fallen leaves that lie around it.

Name: Leavanny
FlavorText: It keeps its eggs warm with heat from fermenting leaves. It also uses leaves to make warm wrappings for Sewaddle.

Name: Leavanny
FlavorText: Upon finding a small Pokémon, it weaves clothing for it from leaves by using the sticky silk secreted from its mouth.

Name: Leavanny
FlavorText: Upon finding a small Pokémon, it weaves clothing for it from leaves, using the cutters on its arms and sticky silk.

Name: Cottonee
FlavorText: Weaving together the cotton of both Cottonee and Eldegoss produces exquisite cloth that’s highly prized by many luxury brands.

Name: Cottonee
FlavorText: It shoots cotton from its body to protect itself. If it gets caught up in hurricane-strength winds, it can get sent to the other side of the Earth.

Name: Cottonee
FlavorText: When attacked, it expels cotton from its body to create a diversion. The cotton it loses grows back in quickly.

Name: Cottonee
FlavorText: To protect itself, it shoots cotton from its body. When it gets wet in the rain, its cotton grows moist and heavy, and it can’t move as well.

Name: Cottonee
FlavorText: Pillows and beds stuffed with cotton exhaled by Cottonee are soft and puffy, light and airy— altogether top quality.

Name: Cottonee
FlavorText: When it finds others of its kind, they all stick together. When enough of them have collected, the mass resembles a cumulonimbus cloud.

Name: Cottonee
FlavorText: Perhaps because they feel more at ease in a group, they stick to others they find. They end up looking like a cloud.

Name: Cottonee
FlavorText: When attacked, it escapes by shooting cotton from its body. The cotton serves as a decoy to distract the attacker.

Name: Cottonee
FlavorText: They go wherever the wind takes them. On rainy days, their bodies are heavier, so they take shelter beneath big trees.

Name: Whimsicott
FlavorText: As long as this Pokémon bathes in sunlight, its cotton keeps growing. If too much cotton fluff builds up, Whimsicott tears it off and scatters it.

Name: Whimsicott
FlavorText: It scatters cotton all over the place as a prank. If it gets wet, it’ll become too heavy to move and have no choice but to answer for its mischief.

Name: Whimsicott
FlavorText: Whimsicott doesn’t live in a fixed location. It floats around on whirling winds, appearing all over the place to perform its mischief.

Name: Whimsicott
FlavorText: This nuisance sneaks into people’s homes, where it hides important things and scatters cotton all over the place.

Name: Whimsicott
FlavorText: This Pokémon appears, riding upon the wind. But if the wind gusts up, it’ll blow the cotton on this Pokémon’s head clean off.

Name: Whimsicott
FlavorText: It rides on the wind and slips into people’s homes. After it has turned a room into a cotton-filled mess, it giggles to itself and takes off.

Name: Whimsicott
FlavorText: Like the wind, it can slip through any gap, no matter how small. It leaves balls of white fluff behind.

Name: Whimsicott
FlavorText: They appear along with whirlwinds. They pull pranks, such as moving furniture and leaving balls of cotton in homes.

Name: Whimsicott
FlavorText: Riding whirlwinds, they appear. These Pokémon sneak through gaps into houses and cause all sorts of mischief.

Name: Petilil
FlavorText: If the leaves on its head are pruned with regularity, this Pokémon can be grown into a fine plump shape.

Name: Petilil
FlavorText: The leaves on its head grow right back even if they fall out. These bitter leaves refresh those who eat them.

Name: Petilil
FlavorText: The leaves on its head are highly valued for medicinal purposes. Dry the leaves in the sun, boil them, and then drink the bitter decoction for remarkably effective relief from fatigue.

Name: Petilil
FlavorText: The deeper the color of a Petilil’s leaves, the healthier the Pokémon is. Petilil sometimes makes its home in a well-tended field or flowerbed.

Name: Petilil
FlavorText: Petilil appears around sources of clean water. Boiling leaves from this Pokémon’s head results in a liquid that’s sometimes used as a bug repellent.

Name: Petilil
FlavorText: They prefer clean water and soil. When the environment they live in turns bad, the whole bunch will up and move to a new area.

Name: Petilil
FlavorText: Some say if you dry the leaves on its head, boil them down, and drink the infusion, your vigor will return, so Petilil is popular with the elderly.

Name: Petilil
FlavorText: By pruning the leaves on its head with regularity, this Pokémon can be grown into a fine plump shape.

Name: Petilil
FlavorText: Although the leaves on its head are bitter enough to cause dizziness, they provide relief from weariness—even more so when boiled.

Name: Petilil
FlavorText: Since they prefer moist, nutrient-rich soil, the areas where Petilil live are known to be good for growing plants.

Name: Petilil
FlavorText: The leaves on its head are very bitter. Eating one of these leaves is known to refresh a tired body.

Name: Lilligant
FlavorText: I suspect that its well-developed legs are the result of a life spent on mountains covered in deep snow. The scent it exudes from its flower crown heartens those in proximity.

Name: Lilligant
FlavorText: No matter how much time and money is spent raising it, its flowers are the most beautiful when they bloom in the wild.

Name: Lilligant
FlavorText: The fragrance of the garland on its head has a relaxing effect, but taking care of it is very difficult.

Name: Lilligant
FlavorText: Essential oils made from Lilligant flowers have a sublime scent, but they’re also staggeringly expensive.

Name: Lilligant
FlavorText: It’s believed that even first-rate gardeners have a hard time getting the flower on a Lilligant’s head to bloom.

Name: Lilligant
FlavorText: It’s well liked by other Pokémon because of its beauty. The flower on its head needs constant care, or it will soon wither and rot.

Name: Lilligant
FlavorText: The fragrance of its flower differs slightly depending on the soil where it grew up. Sniffing the aroma calms your heart and mind.

Name: Lilligant
FlavorText: As soon as it finds a male to be its partner, the beautiful flower on its head darkens, droops, and withers away.

Name: Lilligant
FlavorText: Even veteran Trainers face a challenge in getting its beautiful flower to bloom. This Pokémon is popular with celebrities.

Name: Lilligant
FlavorText: The fragrance of the garland on its head has a relaxing effect. It withers if a Trainer does not take good care of it.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: Though it differs from other Basculin in several respects, including demeanor—this one is gentle—I have categorized it as a regional form given the vast array of shared qualities.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: The power of its jaws is immense—enough to leave teeth marks in iron sheets. Its personality is also extremely vicious.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: These Pokémon form schools with others of the same color. The greatest foe of a school of blue Basculin is a school of red Basculin.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: Known for their violence, these Pokémon have the most fights with schools of red-striped Basculin.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: Blue-striped Basculin used to be a common food source. They apparently have an inoffensive, light flavor.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: Some people call it “the thug of the lake.” Whether the differences in color are meaningful is not yet known.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: Even Basculin, which devours everything it can with its huge jaws, is nothing more than food to organisms stronger than itself.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: It’s so vicious that it’s called the Thug of the River. Yet Basculin is still targeted by predators, such as Dondozo and Bombirdier.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: Its temperament is vicious and aggressive. This Pokémon is also full of vitality and can multiply rapidly before anyone notices.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: In the past, it often appeared on the dinner table. The meat of red-striped Basculin is on the fatty side, and it’s more popular with the youth.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: Anglers love the fight this Pokémon puts up on the hook. And there are always more to catch— many people release them into lakes illicitly.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: When a school of Basculin appears in a lake, everything else disappears, except for Corphish and Crawdaunt. That’s how violent Basculin are.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: Savage, violent Pokémon, red and blue Basculin are always fighting each other over territory.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: Red and blue Basculin usually do not get along, but sometimes members of one school mingle with the other’s school.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: Red- and blue-striped Basculin are very violent and always fighting. They are also remarkably tasty.

Name: Basculin
FlavorText: Red and blue Basculin get along so poorly, they’ll start fighting instantly. These Pokémon are very hostile.

Name: Darumaka
FlavorText: This popular symbol of good fortune will never fall over in its sleep, no matter how it’s pushed or pulled.

Name: Darumaka
FlavorText: It derives its power from fire burning inside its body. If the fire dwindles, this Pokémon will immediately fall asleep.

Name: Darumaka
FlavorText: When it sleeps, it pulls its limbs into its body and its internal fire goes down to 1,100 degrees Fahrenheit.

Name: Darumaka
FlavorText: Darumaka’s droppings are hot, so people used to put them in their clothes to keep themselves warm.

Name: Darumaka
FlavorText: When it sleeps, it pulls its limbs into its body and its internal fire goes down to 1,100° F.

Name: Darumaka
FlavorText: When its internal fire is burning, it cannot calm down and it runs around. When the fire diminishes, it falls asleep.

Name: Darmanitan
FlavorText: Darmanitan takes this form when enraged. It won’t stop spewing flames until its rage has settled, even if its body starts to melt.

Name: Darmanitan
FlavorText: Anger has reignited its atrophied flame sac. This Pokémon spews fire everywhere as it rampages indiscriminately.

Name: Darmanitan
FlavorText: When wounded, it stops moving. It goes as still as stone to meditate, sharpening its mind and spirit.

Name: Darmanitan
FlavorText: Through meditation, it calms its raging spirit and hones its psychic powers.

Name: Darmanitan
FlavorText: This Pokémon’s power level rises along with the temperature of its fire, which can reach 2,500 degrees Fahrenheit.

Name: Darmanitan
FlavorText: The thick arms of this hot-blooded Pokémon can deliver punches capable of obliterating a dump truck.

Name: Darmanitan
FlavorText: Its internal fire burns at 2,500 degrees Fahrenheit, making enough power that it can destroy a dump truck with one punch.

Name: Darmanitan
FlavorText: When one is injured in a fierce battle, it hardens into a stone-like form. Then it meditates and sharpens its mind.

Name: Darmanitan
FlavorText: When weakened in battle, it transforms into a stone statue. Then it sharpens its mind and fights on mentally.

Name: Darmanitan
FlavorText: Its internal fire burns at 2,500° F, making enough power that it can destroy a dump truck with one punch.

Name: Maractus
FlavorText: Once each year, this Pokémon scatters its seeds. They’re jam-packed with nutrients, making them a precious food source out in the desert.

Name: Maractus
FlavorText: With noises that could be mistaken for the rattles of maracas, it creates an upbeat rhythm, startling bird Pokémon and making them fly off in a hurry.

Name: Maractus
FlavorText: Arid regions are their habitat. They move rhythmically, making a sound similar to maracas.

Name: Maractus
FlavorText: It uses an up-tempo song and dance to drive away the bird Pokémon that prey on its flower seeds.

Name: Maractus
FlavorText: When it moves rhythmically, it makes a sound similar to maracas, making the surprised Pokémon flee.

Name: Tirtouga
FlavorText: Tirtouga is considered to be the ancestor of many turtle Pokémon. It was restored to life from a fossil.

Name: Tirtouga
FlavorText: This Pokémon inhabited ancient seas. Although it can only crawl, it still comes up onto land in search of prey.

Name: Tirtouga
FlavorText: Its hunting grounds encompassed a broad area, from the land to more than half a mile deep in the ocean.

Name: Tirtouga
FlavorText: It was restored from an ancient fossil. Tirtouga lived in the sea but came up onto the land to search for prey.

Name: Tirtouga
FlavorText: Reputed to be the ancestor of most turtle Pokémon, it lived in warm seas approximately a hundred million years ago.

Name: Tirtouga
FlavorText: Based on studies of its skeletal structure, it can apparently dive to ocean depths of over half a mile.

Name: Tirtouga
FlavorText: Restored from a fossil, this Pokémon can dive to depths beyond half a mile.

Name: Tirtouga
FlavorText: About 100 million years ago, these Pokémon swam in oceans. It is thought they also went on land to attack prey.

Name: Tirtouga
FlavorText: This Pokémon was restored from a fossil. It swam skillfully and dove to depths beyond half a mile.

Name: Carracosta
FlavorText: This Pokémon emerges from the water in search of prey despite the fact that it moves more slowly on land.

Name: Carracosta
FlavorText: Carracosta completely devours its prey—bones, shells, and all. Because of this, Carracosta’s own shell grows thick and sturdy.

Name: Carracosta
FlavorText: Carracosta eats every last bit of the prey it catches, even the shells and bones, to further strengthen its sturdy shell.

Name: Carracosta
FlavorText: Its jaws are terrifyingly powerful. It could eat Omastar and Omanyte whole and not be bothered in the slightest by their shells.

Name: Carracosta
FlavorText: Active both on land and in the sea, this Pokémon drags its land-based prey into the water to finish it off.

Name: Carracosta
FlavorText: It constructed its sturdy shell by crunching and swallowing the hard shells or bones of its prey.

Name: Carracosta
FlavorText: It could knock out a foe with a slap from one of its developed front appendages and chew it up, shell or bones and all.

Name: Carracosta
FlavorText: They can live both in the ocean and on land. A slap from one of them is enough to open a hole in the bottom of a tanker.

Name: Carracosta
FlavorText: Incredible jaw strength enables them to chew up steel beams and rocks along with their prey.

Name: Ducklett
FlavorText: They are better at swimming than flying, and they happily eat their favorite food, peat moss, as they dive underwater.

Name: Ducklett
FlavorText: When attacked, it uses its feathers to splash water, escaping under cover of the spray.

Name: Ducklett
FlavorText: These bird Pokémon are excellent divers. They swim around in the water eating their favorite food--peat moss.

Name: Swanna
FlavorText: Swanna start to dance at dusk. The one dancing in the middle is the leader of the flock.

Name: Swanna
FlavorText: Despite their elegant appearance, they can flap their wings strongly and fly for thousands of miles.

Name: Swanna
FlavorText: It administers sharp, powerful pecks with its bill. It whips its long neck to deliver forceful repeated strikes.

Name: Deerling
FlavorText: This Pokémon will playfully headbutt those it gets along well with. It has antlers hidden under its flower, so the headbutts are a little painful.

Name: Deerling
FlavorText: Deerling’s scent changes with the seasons, but when the Pokémon is in its Winter Form, it has hardly any scent at all.

Name: Deerling
FlavorText: Deerling have different scents depending on the season. When a distinct grassy smell starts to waft from one, you know that summer has begun.

Name: Deerling
FlavorText: To prevent Deerling from entering their fields, many farmers will have several Lycanroc stand guard, as they are the natural enemy of Deerling.

Name: Deerling
FlavorText: Despite Deerling’s adorable appearance, farmers consider it a nuisance since it loves plant shoots and will eat them all up.

Name: Deerling
FlavorText: Deerling have different scents depending on the season. In early spring, these Pokémon give off a delicate, sweet, and calming scent.

Name: Deerling
FlavorText: Deerling have different scents depending on the season. In this form, Deerling have a softly sweet scent that lingers in the nose.

Name: Deerling
FlavorText: These Pokémon are not shy—they will behave as they please, even in front of people. If you feed one of them, it will quickly take a liking to you.

Name: Deerling
FlavorText: The turning of the seasons changes the color and scent of this Pokémon’s fur. People use it to mark the seasons.

Name: Deerling
FlavorText: Their coloring changes according to the seasons and can be slightly affected by the temperature and humidity as well.

Name: Deerling
FlavorText: The color and scent of their fur changes to match the mountain grass. When they sense hostility, they hide in the grass.

Name: Sawsbuck
FlavorText: Though there are many enthusiasts for Sawsbuck as a species, this seasonal form in particular is not very popular.

Name: Sawsbuck
FlavorText: It’s said that Sawsbuck are calm and easy to tame during the season when they take on this form, so it’s the perfect time to make one your partner.

Name: Sawsbuck
FlavorText: This Pokémon’s leaves can be made into a black tea, the taste of which varies depending on the region of origin. Paldea’s is especially aromatic.

Name: Sawsbuck
FlavorText: There are many Sawsbuck enthusiasts. The thicker and larger the branches and leaves on its antlers, the more majestic the Sawsbuck is thought to be.

Name: Sawsbuck
FlavorText: There are many Sawsbuck enthusiasts. The paler the pink flowers that bloom on its antlers, the more beautiful the Sawsbuck is considered to be.

Name: Sawsbuck
FlavorText: It seems that a Sawsbuck with many flowers on its antlers will grow at a slightly slower pace because the flowers absorb the Pokémon’s nutrients.

Name: Sawsbuck
FlavorText: Sawsbuck in their Autumn Form are known for having very short tempers. The males fight each other incessantly.

Name: Sawsbuck
FlavorText: There are many Sawsbuck enthusiasts. The darker the red of the foliage that hangs from its antlers, the more stylish the Sawsbuck is thought to be.

Name: Sawsbuck
FlavorText: They migrate according to the seasons, so some people call Sawsbuck the harbingers of spring.

Name: Sawsbuck
FlavorText: They migrate according to the seasons. People can tell the season by looking at Sawsbuck’s horns.

Name: Sawsbuck
FlavorText: The plants growing on its horns change according to the season. The leaders of the herd possess magnificent horns.

Name: Foongus
FlavorText: This Pokémon prefers damp places. It spurts out poison spores to repel approaching enemies.

Name: Foongus
FlavorText: There is a theory that the developer of the modern-day Poké Ball really liked Foongus, but this has not been confirmed.

Name: Foongus
FlavorText: The spores released from this Pokémon’s hands are highly poisonous, but when thoroughly dried, the spores can be used as stomach medicine.

Name: Foongus
FlavorText: No one knows what the Poké Ball–like pattern on Foongus means or why Foongus has it.

Name: Foongus
FlavorText: It lures Pokémon with its pattern that looks just like a Poké Ball, then releases poison spores.

Name: Foongus
FlavorText: It lures people in with its Poké Ball pattern, then releases poison spores. Why it resembles a Poké Ball is unknown.

Name: Foongus
FlavorText: It lures Pokémon with its pattern that looks just like a Poké Ball then releases poison spores.

Name: Foongus
FlavorText: For some reason, this Pokémon resembles a Poké Ball. They release poison spores to repel those who try to catch them.

Name: Amoonguss
FlavorText: Amoonguss mimics Poké Balls. It is not yet clear whether this mimicry is effective against other Pokémon.

Name: Amoonguss
FlavorText: Be wary of the poisonous spores it releases. Mushrooms resembling Amoonguss’s caps will grow out of anywhere the spores touch.

Name: Amoonguss
FlavorText: Amoonguss generally doesn’t move much. It tends to stand still near Poké Balls that have been dropped on the ground.

Name: Amoonguss
FlavorText: This Pokémon puffs poisonous spores at its foes. If the spores aren’t washed off quickly, they’ll grow into mushrooms wherever they land.

Name: Amoonguss
FlavorText: It lures prey close by dancing and waving its arm caps, which resemble Poké Balls, in a swaying motion.

Name: Amoonguss
FlavorText: They show off their Poké Ball caps to lure prey, but very few Pokémon are fooled by this.

Name: Amoonguss
FlavorText: It moves the caps on both arms and does a dance to lure prey. It prefers damp places.

Name: Frillish
FlavorText: Legend has it that the residents of a sunken ancient city changed into these Pokémon.

Name: Frillish
FlavorText: It envelops its prey in its veillike arms and draws it down to the deeps, five miles below the ocean’s surface.

Name: Frillish
FlavorText: Its thin, veillike arms have tens of thousands of poisonous stingers. Females have slightly longer stingers.

Name: Frillish
FlavorText: Using the invisible poison spikes on its veillike arms and legs, it paralyzes its enemies and causes them to drown.

Name: Frillish
FlavorText: It wraps its veillike arms and legs around prey swimming by and drags them down to the depths of the ocean.

Name: Frillish
FlavorText: If its veil-like arms stun and wrap a foe, that foe will be dragged miles below the surface, never to return.

Name: Frillish
FlavorText: They paralyze prey with poison, then drag them down to their lairs, five miles below the surface.

Name: Frillish
FlavorText: With its thin, veil-like arms wrapped around the body of its opponent, it sinks to the ocean floor.

Name: Jellicent
FlavorText: Whenever a full moon hangs in the night sky, schools of Jellicent gather near the surface of the sea, waiting for their prey to appear.

Name: Jellicent
FlavorText: Most of this Pokémon’s body composition is identical to sea water. It makes sunken ships its lair.

Name: Jellicent
FlavorText: The crown on its head gets bigger and bigger as it absorbs more and more of the life-force of other creatures.

Name: Jellicent
FlavorText: These Pokémon have body compositions that are mostly identical to seawater. They make their lairs from sunken ships.

Name: Jellicent
FlavorText: Fishermen are terrified of Jellicent. It’s rumored to drag them into the sea and steal their lives away.

Name: Jellicent
FlavorText: Jellicent is always hanging around fancy cruise ships and tankers, hoping to drag away its prey.

Name: Jellicent
FlavorText: The fate of the ships and crew that wander into Jellicent’s habitat: all sunken, all lost, all vanished.

Name: Jellicent
FlavorText: Its body is mostly seawater. It’s said there’s a castle of ships Jellicent have sunk on the seafloor.

Name: Jellicent
FlavorText: They propel themselves by expelling absorbed seawater from their bodies. Their favorite food is life energy.

Name: Alomomola
FlavorText: They float upon the open sea. Many water Pokémon gather in the area around Alomomola.

Name: Alomomola
FlavorText: It gently holds injured and weak Pokémon in its fins. Its special membrane heals their wounds.

Name: Alomomola
FlavorText: The reason it helps Pokémon in a weakened condition is that any Pokémon coming after them may also attack Alomomola.

Name: Alomomola
FlavorText: Fishermen take them along on long voyages, because if you have an Alomomola with you, there’ll be no need for a doctor or medicine.

Name: Alomomola
FlavorText: It uses its special mucus to close the wounds of injured Pokémon. The reason for this behavior remains unknown.

Name: Alomomola
FlavorText: Floating in the open sea is how they live. When they find a wounded Pokémon, they embrace it and bring it to shore.

Name: Alomomola
FlavorText: The special membrane enveloping Alomomola has the ability to heal wounds.

Name: Ferroseed
FlavorText: Mossy caves are their preferred dwellings. Enzymes contained in mosses help Ferroseed’s spikes grow big and strong.

Name: Ferroseed
FlavorText: It defends itself by launching spikes, but its aim isn’t very good at first. Only after a lot of practice will it improve.

Name: Ferroseed
FlavorText: It absorbs the iron it finds in the rock while clinging to the ceiling. It shoots spikes when in danger.

Name: Ferroseed
FlavorText: When threatened, it attacks by shooting a barrage of spikes, which gives it a chance to escape by rolling away.

Name: Ferroseed
FlavorText: They stick their spikes into cave walls and absorb the minerals they find in the rock.

Name: Ferrothorn
FlavorText: Its spikes are harder than steel. This Pokémon crawls across rock walls by stabbing the spikes on its feelers into the stone.

Name: Ferrothorn
FlavorText: This Pokémon scrapes its spikes across rocks, and then uses the tips of its feelers to absorb the nutrients it finds within the stone.

Name: Ferrothorn
FlavorText: They attach themselves to cave ceilings, firing steel spikes at targets passing beneath them.

Name: Ferrothorn
FlavorText: By swinging around its three spiky feelers and shooting spikes, it can obliterate an opponent.

Name: Ferrothorn
FlavorText: It fights by swinging around its three spiky feelers. A hit from these steel spikes can reduce a boulder to rubble.

Name: Litwick
FlavorText: The younger the life this Pokémon absorbs, the brighter and eerier the flame on its head burns.

Name: Litwick
FlavorText: The flame on its head keeps its body slightly warm. This Pokémon takes lost children by the hand to guide them to the spirit world.

Name: Litwick
FlavorText: Litwick shines a light that absorbs the life energy of people and Pokémon, which becomes the fuel that it burns.

Name: Litwick
FlavorText: While shining a light and pretending to be a guide, it leeches off the life force of any who follow it.

Name: Litwick
FlavorText: Its flame is usually out, but it starts shining when it absorbs life force from people or Pokémon.

Name: Lampent
FlavorText: It lurks in cities, pretending to be a lamp. Once it finds someone whose death is near, it will trail quietly after them.

Name: Lampent
FlavorText: This Pokémon appears just before someone passes away, so it’s feared as an emissary of death.

Name: Lampent
FlavorText: It arrives near the moment of death and steals spirit from the body.

Name: Lampent
FlavorText: The spirits it absorbs fuel its baleful fire. It hangs around hospitals waiting for people to pass on.

Name: Lampent
FlavorText: This ominous Pokémon is feared. Through cities it wanders, searching for the spirits of the fallen.

Name: Chandelure
FlavorText: In homes illuminated by Chandelure instead of lights, funerals were a constant occurrence— or so it’s said.

Name: Chandelure
FlavorText: This Pokémon haunts dilapidated mansions. It sways its arms to hypnotize opponents with the ominous dancing of its flames.

Name: Chandelure
FlavorText: The spirits burned up in its ominous flame lose their way and wander this world forever.

Name: Chandelure
FlavorText: Being consumed in Chandelure’s flame burns up the spirit, leaving the body behind.

Name: Chandelure
FlavorText: It absorbs a spirit, which it then burns. By waving the flames on its arms, it puts its foes into a hypnotic trance.

Name: Heatmor
FlavorText: A flame serves as its tongue, melting through the hard shell of Durant so that Heatmor can devour their insides.

Name: Heatmor
FlavorText: There’s a hole in its tail that allows it to draw in the air it needs to keep its fire burning. If the hole gets blocked, this Pokémon will fall ill.

Name: Heatmor
FlavorText: It draws in air through its tail, transforms it into fire, and uses it like a tongue. It melts Durant and eats them.

Name: Heatmor
FlavorText: Using their very hot, flame-covered tongues, they burn through Durant’s steel bodies and consume their insides.

Name: Heatmor
FlavorText: It breathes through a hole in its tail while it burns with an internal fire. Durant is its prey.

Name: Larvesta
FlavorText: In ancient times, Larvesta was worshiped as the emissary of the sun. However, it was also viewed as a burden since it often caused forest fires.

Name: Larvesta
FlavorText: This Pokémon was called the Larva That Stole the Sun. The fire Larvesta spouts from its horns can cut right through a sheet of iron.

Name: Larvesta
FlavorText: Larvesta’s body is warm all over. It spouts fire from the tips of its horns to intimidate predators and scare prey.

Name: Larvesta
FlavorText: The people of ancient times believed that Larvesta fell from the sun.

Name: Larvesta
FlavorText: It protects itself with flame. Long years ago, people believed Larvesta had a nest on the sun.

Name: Larvesta
FlavorText: When battling opponents, it sprays fire from its five horns. The max temperature of the flames can reach nearly 5,500 degrees Fahrenheit.

Name: Larvesta
FlavorText: The base of volcanoes is where they make their homes. They shoot fire from their five horns to repel attacking enemies.

Name: Larvesta
FlavorText: Said to have been born from the sun, it spews fire from its horns and encases itself in a cocoon of fire when it evolves.

Name: Larvesta
FlavorText: This Pokémon was believed to have been born from the sun. When it evolves, its entire body is engulfed in flames.

Name: Volcarona
FlavorText: This Pokémon scatters burning scales. Most of the danger of these scales is not in their heat—it’s in the way they rob the surrounding air of oxygen.

Name: Volcarona
FlavorText: Its burning body causes it to be unpopular in hot parts of the world, but in cold ones, Volcarona is revered as an embodiment of the sun.

Name: Volcarona
FlavorText: This Pokémon emerges from a cocoon formed of raging flames. Ancient murals depict Volcarona as a deity of fire.

Name: Volcarona
FlavorText: Volcarona scatters burning scales. Some say it does this to start fires. Others say it’s trying to rescue those that suffer in the cold.

Name: Volcarona
FlavorText: According to legends, it was hatched from a flaming cocoon to save people and Pokémon that were suffering from the cold.

Name: Volcarona
FlavorText: As it flies, it scatters its flaming scales. It was feared by ancient people, who referred to it as “the rage of the sun.”

Name: Volcarona
FlavorText: When volcanic ash darkened the atmosphere, it is said that Volcarona’s fire provided a replacement for the sun.

Name: Volcarona
FlavorText: A sea of fire engulfs the surroundings of their battles, since they use their six wings to scatter their ember scales.

Name: Volcarona
FlavorText: Thought to be an embodiment of the sun, it appeared during a bitterly cold winter and saved Pokémon from freezing.

Name: Virizion
FlavorText: It darts around opponents with a flurry of quick movements, slicing them up with its horns.

Name: Virizion
FlavorText: A legend tells of this Pokémon working together with Cobalion and Terrakion to protect the Pokémon of the Unova region.

Name: Virizion
FlavorText: Legends say this Pokémon confounded opponents with its swift movements.

Name: Virizion
FlavorText: Its head sprouts horns as sharp as blades. Using whirlwind-like movements, it confounds and swiftly cuts opponents.

Name: Virizion
FlavorText: This Pokémon fought humans in order to protect its friends. Legends about it continue to be passed down.

Name: Reshiram
FlavorText: According to myth, if people ignore truth and let themselves become consumed by greed, Reshiram will arrive to burn their kingdoms down.

Name: Reshiram
FlavorText: Flames spew from its tail as it flies through the sky like a jet airplane. It’s said that this Pokémon will scorch the world.

Name: Reshiram
FlavorText: When Reshiram’s tail flares, the heat energy moves the atmosphere and changes the world’s weather.

Name: Reshiram
FlavorText: This legendary Pokémon can scorch the world with fire. It helps those who want to build a world of truth.

Name: Reshiram
FlavorText: This Pokémon appears in legends. It sends flames into the air from its tail, burning up everything around it.

Name: Keldeo
FlavorText: The power that lay hidden in its body now covers its horn, turning it into a sword that can slice through anything.

Name: Keldeo
FlavorText: Keldeo has strengthened its resolve for battle, filling its body with power and changing its form.

Name: Keldeo
FlavorText: They say that Keldeo must survive harsh battles and fully develop the horn on its forehead before this Pokémon’s true power will awaken.

Name: Keldeo
FlavorText: Cobalion, Terrakion, and Virizion taught this Pokémon how to fight. It dashes across the world, seeking more opportunities to further its training.

Name: Keldeo
FlavorText: When it is resolute, its body fills with power and it becomes swifter. Its jumps are then too fast to follow.

Name: Keldeo
FlavorText: It crosses the world, running over the surfaces of oceans and rivers. It appears at scenic waterfronts.

Name: Keldeo
FlavorText: By blasting water from its hooves, it can glide across water. It excels at using leg moves while battling.

Name: Chespin
FlavorText: Such a thick shell of wood covers its head and back that even a direct hit from a truck wouldn’t faze it.

Name: Chespin
FlavorText: The quills on its head are usually soft. When it flexes them, the points become so hard and sharp that they can pierce rock.

Name: Quilladin
FlavorText: They strengthen their lower bodies by running into one another. They are very kind and won’t start fights.

Name: Quilladin
FlavorText: It relies on its sturdy shell to deflect predators’ attacks. It counterattacks with its sharp quills.

Name: Chesnaught
FlavorText: When it takes a defensive posture with its fists guarding its face, it could withstand a bomb blast.

Name: Chesnaught
FlavorText: Its Tackle is forceful enough to flip a 50-ton tank. It shields its allies from danger with its own body.

Name: Fennekin
